<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Appearance and Visual Character</h3>
<p>Red Bordeaux wines display a spectrum from deep ruby-purple in youth to brick-orange garnet with age. Young wines often show almost opaque concentration, indicating high phenolic extraction from extended maceration. The wine's "legs" or glycerol tears suggest moderate to high alcohol (typically 12.5-14.5% ABV). White Bordeaux ranges from pale gold to deep amber, with barrel-aged examples showing richer hues that hint at their oak influence and potential for cellaring.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Aromatic Complexity</h3>
<p>Bordeaux's aromatic profile develops in distinct layers. <strong>Primary fruit aromas</strong> in Left Bank Cabernet Sauvignon-dominant blends feature blackcurrant (cassis), dark plum, and cedar, while Right Bank Merlot-based wines emphasize red cherry, plum, and chocolate. <strong>Secondary fermentation notes</strong> include subtle yeast autolysis and malolactic conversion creating creamy, buttery undertones. <strong>Tertiary aging aromas</strong> develop magnificently: leather, tobacco leaf, graphite minerality, dried herbs like thyme and rosemary, and classic "pencil shavings" cedar from American and French oak integration.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Palate Structure and Mouthfeel</h3>
<p>Premium Bordeaux exhibits medium to full body with remarkable balance. Acidity ranges from moderate to high (pH 3.3-3.6), providing aging potential and food compatibility. Tannins vary by bank: Left Bank wines show firm, structured tannins from Cabernet Sauvignon and Petit Verdot, while Right Bank expressions offer softer, more approachable tannins from Merlot dominance. The texture evolves from initially grippy to silky-smooth with proper cellaring.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Flavor Profile and Terroir Expression</h3>
<p>Bordeaux's flavor complexity reflects its unique terroir. Expect layers of dark fruit compote, earthy forest floor, wet limestone minerality, and distinctive <em>goût de terroir</em>—that unmistakable sense of place. Spice notes include black pepper, clove, and vanilla from oak, while mineral qualities range from graphite (Left Bank gravel) to clay-driven earthiness (Right Bank). Premium examples show remarkable flavor persistence and evolution in the glass.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Finish and Quality Indicators</h3>
<p>Exceptional Bordeaux displays a long, lingering finish (30+ seconds) with evolving flavors. Quality markers include seamless tannin integration, balanced alcohol that doesn't overpower, persistent fruit concentration, and complex tertiary development. The aftertaste should reveal additional layers—perhaps dried flowers, exotic spices, or mineral nuances—that weren't immediately apparent on the initial palate.</p>

